Daily Cases

https://beta.isdscotland.org/find-publications-and-data/conditions-and-diseases/cancer/cancer-incidence-in-scotland/28-april-2020/

Identifying the number of cases diagnosed each day from 1994 to 2018. This includes all three brain cancer types specified in the data (Malignant Brain Cancer, Malignant Brain Cancer including the pituitary gland, craniopharyngeal duct and pineal gland and Non Malignant cancer including the pituitary gland, craniopharyngeal duct and pineal gland).

I decided to find the mean number of incidences of non-malignant brain tumours in order to impute the missing values with it. According to Wu, Khorshidi, Aickelin, Edib and Peate (2019), simple mean mutation is a better method of handling missing values than deletion when dealing with breast cancer data. https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s13755-019-0082-4

updated_cancer_incidences %>% 
  filter(hb_label == "SCOTLAND") %>% 
  filter(age_label == "Number of registrations: All Ages") %>% 
  filter(site_label == "Non-malignant brain cancer (incl pituitary gland, craniopharyngeal duct and pineal gland)") %>% 
  filter(sex_label == "All Persons") %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  summarise(mean_incidence = mean(incidence_no_and_rates)) 
#Filtering out malignant brain cancer and total cancer cases because I am trying to ascertain if the malignant brain cancer including pituitary gland etc and non-malignant brain cancer including the pituitary gland etc combine to make the same total as the all brain and CNS tumours incidence column.  
scotland_incidences_all_types <- updated_cancer_incidences %>% 
  filter(hb_label == "SCOTLAND") %>% 
  filter(age_label == "Number of registrations: All Ages") %>% 
  filter(sex_label == "All Persons") %>% 
  filter(site_label != "Malignant brain cancer") %>% 
  filter(site_label != "All brain and CNS tumours (malignant and non-malignant)") %>% 
  mutate(incidence_no_and_rates = coalesce(incidence_no_and_rates, 534, na.rm = TRUE))

The total number of cases of malignant and non-malignant brain tumours including those in the pituitary gland, craniopharyngeal duct and pineal gland is the same as the total number of tumours found in the brain and central nervous system data. However, it was necessary to identify the total number of cases by hand in order to impute the missing values from 1994 to 1999 in the non-malignant cancer data with the mean. The data for total tumours for those years was missing and so had to be calculated as above.

scotland_incidences_all_types %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(total_cases = sum(incidence_no_and_rates)) %>% 
  mutate(avg_diagnosed_per_day = total_cases / 365) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(year, avg_diagnosed_per_day)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE, color = "brown3") + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1994, 2018, by = 1)) + 
  labs(title = "Estimated Daily Diagnosis in Scotland from 1993 to 2017", 
       subtitle = "Malignant and non-malignant brain tumours") + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 0.9)) + 
  xlab("Year of Diagnosis") + 
  ylab("Estimated New Cases Each Day") + 
  theme(
  plot.title = title.theme, 
  plot.subtitle = subtitle.theme, 
  axis.title = x.axis.theme)

Percentage of the Scottish population

As of mid 2018, the Scottish population was 5,438,100 (National Records of Scotland, https://www.nrscotland.gov.uk/files/statistics/rgar/2018/rgar18.pdf). The number of cases diagnosed in 2018 was 966.

The percentage of the Scottish population in 2018 diagnosed with a brain tumour was 0.018%. In 2000, the percentage of the population diagnosed with a brain tumour was 0.016%. The difference is pretty minor, but see above for a closer look at estimated daily cases of brain tumours from 1993 to 1997.

Survival

Net survival is an estimate of the probability that the average patient will be alive at a given time after diagnosis, after controlling for other causes of death.

£15038718 spent on Brain cancer research in 2018/2019 (6.55%) £35439980 spent on Leukaemia research in 2018/2019 (15.43%)

In 2012/2013, only £6 million was spent on Brain cancer research. The allocated budget for brain tumour research is growing, but there is still a bridge to gap between this region and research into other cancers. This may be an important factor in reducing the preventable deaths that still occur for those diagnosed with a brain tumour.

#Net survival of males aged from 15 to 99 at 1 and 5 years after the diagnosis. 
joined %>% 
  select(cancer_site_grouping, calendar_period_of_diagnosis, sex, age_group, years_since_diagnosis, 
         net_survival_percent) %>% 
  mutate(net_survival_percent = as.double(net_survival_percent)) %>%  
  mutate(years_since_diagnosis = as.factor(years_since_diagnosis)) %>% 
  filter(sex == "Male") %>% 
  filter(calendar_period_of_diagnosis == "2013-2017" | 
            calendar_period_of_diagnosis == "2008-2012") %>% 
  filter(age_group == "15-99") %>% 
  filter(years_since_diagnosis != 10) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(years_since_diagnosis, net_survival_percent, fill = cancer_site_grouping)) + 
  geom_bar(stat= "identity", position = "dodge") + 
  facet_wrap(~ calendar_period_of_diagnosis) + 
  labs(title = "Brain and CNS Tumour and Leukaemia Net Survival (Male)", 
       subtitle = "Estimated probablity of survival for 1 year and 5 years after diagnosis") + 
  xlab("Years Since Diagnosis") + 
  ylab("Net Survival (%)") + 
  theme(
  plot.title = title.theme, 
  plot.subtitle = subtitle.theme, 
  axis.title = x.axis.theme) + 
  guides(fill = guide_legend(title = "Cancer Site")) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 100, by = 5)) +

There was missing data in the 10 year survival rates of brain tumours, however there is data for the number of deaths within 10 years of a diagnosis of brain cancer. The number of deaths decreased slightly in the 2013-2017 grouping when compared to the 2008-2012 grouping, suggesting more people are surviving brain cancer for longer. Over this time period, 78% of deaths were in those over the age of 54, suggesting death may be more likely to occur in those over 54. However it is important to note that those aged over 54 made up 68% of the recorded cases in 2017, so the higher number of deaths seen in patients over 54 may be in part to their large representation in the data.

Over the period of 2014 to 2018, the risk of death per 100,000 people at risk varied across SIMD quintiles. For those in the second least deprived quintile the mortality rate was highest at 8.3, however the second most deprived quintile is not far behind at 8.2. The lowest mortality rate was in the most deprived quintile, with a rate of 6.6.

Patient Experiences

In 2018, the Scottish Adult Neuro-Oncology Network published an audit with some statistics regarding patient experience. The target for 30 day mortality rate is below 5%. The only region to be over the target was Aberdeen at 9.8%. After surgery, imaging should be done within 3 days to measure surgical performance and determine necessary treatment. The target is 90%, however both Aberdeen and Dundee were under this 90% target.
